Parliament does not support the amendment that gives Tymoshenko freedom
Today, the Parliament of Ukraine in the course of amendments to the Criminal Procedure Code rejected an attempt to cancel the article according to which the leader of the opposition, Yulia Tymoshenko, was convicted.
The amendment, which would lead to the release of the imprisoned former prime minister, was rejected during the second reading of the draft law on the mitigation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was deemed unprofitable.
The verdict is not yet final; the court will consider Tymoshenko’s appeal in December.
Tymoshenko argues that the sentence is a political revenge of the regime; in the West, the process was also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal Article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, under which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 Members of Parliament.
It would require 226 votes to ratify it.
