Ambassador to the EU Vice-President:
The Czechs have a reputation for being unwilling and skeptical of the euro.
“The Lisbon Treaty has caused significant differences between individual organizations.”
“I didn’t expect such a brutal war.”
"It will take five or six years before the situation stabilizes, calms down and all players get used to their new roles," EU Ambassador Milena Vicenova began her lecture at the law school.
She demonstrated how much she adheres to her motto “Clear and open about Europe” in the first part of her lecture, where she described the individual EU institutions and the relationship between them so simply and clearly that many lecturers from the law faculty of the CU would be envious.
Moreover, Vicenova praised the work of the new permanent President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first, critics said he was an ordinary gray office mouse who could not perform any role; I must say, everyone was amazed at how well he handled his role."
“He is a person who can listen to twenty-seven member countries at the same time, who is great at communicating with them and who has a clear idea of which direction the EU should be moving in.”
She explained her new position as a representative for international relations and security as an answer to the question: "Who is the European Union? What number do I need to call?"; that is, as an important step towards unification and greater transparency of the Union's policies with regard to countries such as China or India.
No one is going to ban our cheeses.
Vicenova continued to focus on a programme that is key to the EU in the past, present and near future.
She called the Czech Presidency a success in the past year.
The Czechs dealt with the impending financial crisis; they overcame the crisis and organized the Eastern Partnership summit.
She said that the resignation of the government at the time was a negative phenomenon that caused considerable damage to the Czech Republic.
Currently, Czech representatives in the EU are very busy.
As the ambassador said, both the presidency and the subsequent financial crisis have caused the ongoing fermentation.
In addition, a new seven-year EU budget needs to be adopted, which is very difficult given the current crisis.
Whether the budget will be scarce and economical, which areas will be preferred; which countries will receive more support and which less; all these issues are in the forthcoming programme.
The ambassador recalled the key slogans that she brought to Brussels: "About Europe, understandable language".
“I really don’t like abbreviations, foreign words and jargon that no one understands.
As citizens can understand, people in Brussels are not trying to sell curved or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes, or that someone is going to ban our cheese varieties.
It is also going to make more effective use of the EU environment and attract more Czechs to European organisations.
Multi-speed Europe is our future
The ambassador claims that the Czechs are considered Euro-sceptics; as well as people who note the negative rather than the positive sides of things.
She wants more representatives of the Czech Republic to be involved in European organizations.
She believes that this is due to several factors: for example, the modesty of our candidates and their inability to write motivational letters; at the same time with little support from the Czech side.
Along with the successful Czech Presidency, she noted the power and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me, when I meet someone from Poland and Hungary and a Slovak joins us, the Frenchman next to me says, 'Hey, what's the meeting, the Visegrad group again?' and he's not even happy about it.'
In the future, the Vicenova Union expects mainly new strict rules for the budgetary policies of the member states.
Compared to the new European Federation, it considers the idea of a two-speed, if not a multi-speed Europe, more realistic.
“We have countries both inside and outside the Eurozone.”
“We have a Schengen zone and we already have an institution of enhanced cooperation.”
“For the first time, it was said that countries that want to unite, while those that don’t want to can stay apart.”
“The number of such institutions will grow; it will be a truly two-speed Europe,” Vicenova expects.
In this regard, she stressed the role of both the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in promoting the rule that all EU-wide issues should be discussed by all participating countries, and not only those in the euro area.
Brand History:
Innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence.
If someone wants to find the word that best expresses the IMB strategy, the closest is likely to be “long-lasting.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The company’s longevity was laid down by its first boss, dreamer Thomas J. Watson-senior.
He believed in his motto that many world problems can be easily solved if people want to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant unfolded (as well as the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began publishing in 1935).
What’s more, it was the foundation of a corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means a constant move towards the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, although it was not afraid to change everything around it.
In our first hundred years, this has allowed us to transform technology, business and company.
In the second hundred years, we hope to achieve even more,” says Samuel J. Palmizano, current CEO of the company, on the occasion of the anniversary.
Complicated system
