IBM's history: from a cheese knife to space flights.
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago. Its original name "Computation, Tabulation, Recording Corporation" was quite complex.
It took the name IBM in 1924. Originally, it was called the brand used for the company's offices in Canada and South America.
The foundations of the future of IBM were laid by the merger of four companies, whose history begins in the 1880s.
They possessed technologies such as the legendary "table clock", i.e., a clock that records the time when employees come and go from work.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Runlett Flint, who also headed the board of trustees until 1930.
Flint hired Thomas J. Watson, the director of a rival company, to help him run the company.
The CEO then pushed IBM’s founder into the shadows – Watson’s ideas remain the basis of an immovable corporate culture and individuality.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the production and sale of various equipment for the business – from cheese knives and meat cutters to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson’s leadership, revenue doubled to $9 million, and the company began large-scale expansion across all continents.
Watson became so important to the company that almost forty years later, his son, Thomas Watson Jr., took his place as CEO.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both IBM employees and computers helped NASA control space flights — to Mercury, Saturn, and 1969 — a human flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM Line System/360.
The classic PC that defined the computer standards of the time, called IBM 5150, appeared on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the production of computers to the Chinese company Lenovo, at the same time buying the consulting branch PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus fully concentrating on consulting and services with high added value.
Over the past three years, IBM has achieved great success with its Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to use technology wisely in areas where it has not yet been planned, and to improve the road situation and urban management.
In the field of commerce, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps businessmen control the entire trading cycle.
The tradition of IBM is strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country to be located simultaneously in Central and Eastern Europe, IBM founded its branch in 1932.
Today, IBM CZ also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters of Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague, where a world-class research group on speech recognition also operates.
