The dynamics of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was strictly limited, travel agencies of the time mainly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, on holidays Czech tourists went to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia. Then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which entailed significant restrictions on the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual trips to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation from that country was necessary; otherwise, an individual trip was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered trips to the West, but it was either necessary to stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or to have "good friends" at the agency.
And that's not all.
Currency permits were required for travel to the West and were not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without currency permission it was impossible to obtain cash (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most often the Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the appearance of a large number of cottages and summer houses, this habit remains to this day.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic thus experienced a real revolution.
While before 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were the culmination of our travels, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are no longer aware of is that until 1989 we could not freely visit the most popular Croatia today, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, the need for a visa to the neighbouring countries of Western Europe was abolished. This gave rise to a huge wave of short trips mainly to Vienna and Germany.
Czechoslovaks could not get enough of traveling to the West. Everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents, as their income at the time was not enough for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring your own food (canned, salads, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech koruna. Decades later, our tourists can finally freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income increased, which led to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights operated by charter airlines. Compared to the past, flights have now become incredibly cheap thanks to the ability to order wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all the developed countries of the world except the United States. This made our travels even easier.
The next significant event in the history of travel after the revolution occurred in 2000. Great demand led to the historically first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have been delivering Czech tourists to warm exotic countries. This winter flights from the Czech Republic will be sent to twelve exotic destinations.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, occurred in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. canceled the visa requirement for Czech tourists. Our country has thus joined the most developed countries of the world forever.
For the first time in history in 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history they spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for vacations abroad, including their spending at the destination.
