In the end, it became famous around the world in 1973 for its legendary four-cylinder BMW tower and its sister – a bowl-shaped building.
The pavilion, designed as a building for temporary exhibitions, was moved to the Swiss Garden near Vienna's South Station, converted and opened as a 20th-century museum in 1962 - and is often referred to as the "House of the 20th Century" for this reason.
In any case, the building was not suitable for the museum for technical and spatial reasons - it did not have walls on which to hang works of art, and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until modern art in Vienna received a new home.
The house has been empty since 2001, and its condition is getting worse and worse.
The architect Adolf Krishanitz has to date restored the pavilion, which was called the "House of the 21st century" and will be used as a museum of modern art.
This museum is the branch of the Belvedere Museum, which will open the first exhibition on Tuesday evening - in every sense a joyful event.
Agnes Husslein-Arko, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007, contributed to the new venture.
Husslein-Arko, a graduate of the Faculty of Art History with a brilliant career as a sculptor in her youth, who worked at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and eventually became the founder and director of the Museum of Modernity in Salzburg, has convinced politicians and custodians to continue the reconstruction.
The new museum was to accommodate the permanent exhibition of Fritz Votruba Foundation, a cafe and a bookshop along with modern art. An office building was also to be built.
Strict control & limited budget
Krishanitz was then an ideal candidate for the project.
He was known, of course, for the restoration and expansion of the Vienna Secession by Josef Albrich, and won the competition, but he also studied with Schwanzer at the Vienna University of Technology, and the pavilion was an "extremely important place" for him to attend exhibitions "almost every week".
He knew the original design and the tasks that stood in front of the building, a building that had already lost some of its grandeur and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and transformed.
The problems that arose during the last redevelopment were much more serious. The building was an "energy absorber", says Krishanitz.
Window profiles on the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade were replaced, fiberglass reinforced safety glass was inserted, and the glass roof was replaced with high-strength safety glass.
The steel linings of the thermal bridge were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos was removed from the ceilings.
The two lower floors have created space for a new use of the building, a fallen light well between the building and the street provides lighting - a practically new building, but still an elegant Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors were preserved, and the building was painted in the old red-brown color of corrosion protection.
The movie theater is the same as it used to be.
