An intense and very good new book by Peter Englund, Beauty and Grief: A Personal History of the First World War, begins with a long list of actors from whom the heart is dying.
Here’s a tip on how to read on: Carefully cut out this page and use it as a bookmark.
You will get to know these people very closely as Mr. Englund tells them, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon, when, like one of these men and women, you get off the road and get lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he wrote now is unusual, he describes it, quite accurately, as "a work on anti-history."
It has few known names, important treaties or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors, clever journalists, or discussions of tactics and combat equipment.
It's not so much a book about what it was, he explains, as a "book about what it looked like." It's about "feelings, impressions, experiences and the state of mind."
Beauty and Sorrow brought together 20 years of military experience of more or less inconspicuous men and women on both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and botanical scientists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and servants.
Some of these people will be heroes.
Someone gets captured, loses an arm or leg, goes crazy or dies.
Their lives flicker here like church candles: new ones are added to many others, and some at this time will be extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
It is also an amendment to the notion that the First World War was only a heavy trench war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and sorrow" skilfully gives a panorama of other theaters of hostilities: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
