The Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Study You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Bering Breivik was an ordinary guy exposing his anti-immigration views online.
Breivik, who confessed to committing a mass murder in Norway in July that claimed the lives of 77 people, appeared at his first open court hearing on Monday.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was far from alone on the web: he spent a lot of time preparing for an attack on his computer, communicating with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, the researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
It's easy - you just have to go to Facebook.
“We realized that it’s not hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European cyber-populism at the British DEMOS Research Centre.
The stock of personal data on Facebook is so large, Bartlett says, that researchers could easily use the site’s advertising tool to single out the necessary demographic with scientific accuracy — that marketers have been doing for several years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million right-wing fans across Europe and then pitched them an ad, but instead of showing a new group or a diet product, the ad offered the user a survey that asked questions about their education level, attitudes to violence, and optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 members of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – even without leaving the office.
“It’s a completely new way of doing research,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not so striking: online supporters of right-wing groups - most often young men, dissatisfied with immigration.
But unexpectedly, “those who combine their online activity with offline activity are smarter, more democratic, and less aggressive than those who just hide behind a monitor.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study everything in the world – from health issues to social trends that are expressed in Likes, wall posts, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three posts a day, Facebook’s “super-actual information” is causing a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles titled the site by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it provides an opportunity to study people who can’t be approached on the street with a notebook.
“In the past, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them.”
“You would have to join the party and they would never have accepted you,” Bartlett says.
“Facebook eliminates all of this – you address them directly.”
Others say that through this site it would be possible to identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunk exploits on Facebook were significantly more at risk of alcoholism than students who remained silent about it.
Moreno suggests that students’ peers, such as their dormitory mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often updates drunk statuses.
“You can’t solve the problem without identifying it,” said Dimitri Christokis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior and Development at Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
"We have found a way to identify children from a risk group that we would not have otherwise detected."
Facebook also constantly retrieves various types of data about its users.
The data processing team of the site processed the statistics of the status of relations and Valentine's Day, the turnout of voters in the middle of the term in 2010, as well as the National Happiness Index (using mainly information that only they have access to - the champions of cyber freedom have long insisted on the generalization of the data).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – in exchange for being able to play Scrubble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become participants in a study they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined norms for conducting offline research, online data is publicly available.
“I don’t think a lot of users have even thought about the fact that a researcher can monitor their profiles,” says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a study he conducted in 2006 using public student pages on Facebook.
“As far as they could tell, it was just between them and their friends.”
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that the object of the study is extremely honest.
On Facebook it is impossible to know how much information in the profile and on the user’s page is true.
