7 Lessons From Steve Jobs' Missing Interview Shown in Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans may consider the biggest discovery in a recently-discovered interview that they remembered in anticipation of preliminary shows in major markets this week is how much this creative mind understood in business processes and manufacturing technologies.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer and considered himself a hippie, but he was also a keen organizer and modernizer of the production process, who believed that many business leaders suffered from “the disease of thinking that a really great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] a great idea is a great deal of work and a great product is separated from a huge amount of work.”
Back in 1995, Bob Kringley created the television series Triumph of the Nerds about the advent of a personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs for a unique lengthy conversation.
By that time, it had been about 10 years since Jobs was kicked out of Apple, and he had already worked at his new computer company NeXT in anticipation of the massive development of the Internet.
While a small portion of Kringly’s interview was used in the Nerds, he says the originals of the interview were missing during transportation.
It was only after Jobs’ death that a complete VHS copy was found in the director’s garage.
This footage, slightly edited, became the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which airs at Landmark Theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred of detailed interviews, Jobs seems unusually willing to lay out his technology philosophy and business strategy here.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In four different moments during the interview, there are large intervals between questions and answers - reflections of 10-15 seconds, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to say the exact same thing.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems irritated by Kringle’s questions, causing him to move faster to questions or phenomena of greater importance.
In the pre-Pixar era, the iPods and iPhones Lost interview is something sinisterly prophetic when Jobs evaluates what he sees different companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of information technology.
It's one thing to read about the posthumous assessments of Jobs' work, but there's something vulnerable and inspiring about Jobs that we see here, an alarming dreamer on the threshold of greatness.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Shortly after he said it all here, he went and did it.
A brief summary of the seven significant findings of the Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"All the time in business, I've been asking, 'Why are you doing this?' And the answers you always get are, 'Oh, that's just how it's done.'
No one knows why they do what they do, no one thinks in business very deeply.
That's what I found out.
Jobs continues to describe in detail his attempts to streamline reporting at Apple.
Disturbed by the way of recording expenses, often starting with “standard expenses” that were taken off the ceiling and then adjusted using “add-on”, he created an automated structure that ensured that they could track business expenses down to the smallest detail.
A joke about the Pope:
Jobs details the “blue box” he made with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to effectively hack into a phone company and call long distances for free.
A lot has been written about the device before, but Jobs’ euphoria here when describing the blue box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the box using a phone machine, ordering a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another until as many stations as possible were connected.
“We’ve covered the globe half a dozen times and you’ve been yelling at the phone machine, and it broke into the neighboring phone machine a minute later,” Jobs says with a smile.
“We were young, and all we learned was that we could fabricate something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us knew a little bit, but we could craft a little thing that could control a big thing — it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple could ever have appeared without it.
Jobs goes on to describe in detail one famous invention, which he and Wozniak practically managed by calling the Vatican through a blue box at midnight and asking the Pope to call, trying his best to copy Henry Kissinger.
When different members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the Pope himself was picked up to answer the phone.
On the love of technology (and the cold name of Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to assemble the frequency meter, he found Bill Hulett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“It had a strong impact on me, it was the only company I saw at that age, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how well they treat their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees visiting the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the very first desktop computer.”
He was the size of a suitcase, he had a small monitor with an electron beam tube, and I fell in love with him.
I often went to HP when I was a teenager and I circled around that car and wrote programs for it.
About Improvised Innovation:
In several interviews, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
At the dawn of his career, when he went to sell a handful of mounting plates, one buyer asked him to assemble an entire computer.
Working only 30 days on credit, he had to think about assembling and delivering ready-made devices.
Later at Apple, he recalls the difficulties he faced while developing a computer mouse:
"I remember the furious arguments ... they were screaming at me that it would take five years [to collect a mouse that would cost $300] and I was full of it and I went out and found a designer."
Ninety days later we had a mouse that we were able to collect for $15, which was incredibly reliable.
The big companies that are losing energy:
Long before he headed Apple’s renaissance, Jobs accurately predicted how many industry leaders were mistaken in seeing the situation and would lose control of their market share.
“Suppose you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make the best copy or printer, and what?”
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company does not become more successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [these are the types of people] who eventually come to lead companies, and the people who make the product are pushed out of the decision-making platform.
The genius of the product that led to this monopolistic position is being pushed out by people who have no idea of the difference between good and bad products – the skill required.
This is what happened to Xerox.
Xerox could take over the entire information technology industry.
It could have been 10 times bigger, it could have been Microsoft in the 90s.
They were defeated by victory.
Innovation as an art form:
“A great idea is separated from a great product by a huge amount of skill ... when you spin a great idea, it changes and grows.”
You will learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises you need to make – some things you won’t be able to make electrons, glass, robots, or factories.
You need to keep 5,000 ideas in your head – these concepts – connecting them all together.
Ultimately, it all boils down to taste — it all boils down to trying to express yourself in the best that people have ever produced, and later — trying to bring that to what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've always been ashamed to steal great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh famous was that the people who worked on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happened to become the best IT specialists in the world.
If it weren’t for information technology, they’d be doing amazing things in other areas.
