How to Catch a Lie
A quick look at the latest headlines shows just how serious and pervasive deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential nominee Herman Kane is busy challenging allegations of sexual harassment by several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
The administration of the University of Pennsylvania has been charged with false testimony as they allegedly concealed that the retired football coach had raped the boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught telling U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar while the microphone was on.
Lying destroys careers and shakes countries.
New York congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner has made a fool of himself by denying his credentials, which was quickly denied by incontestable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with financial fraud during a campaign to cover up extramarital affairs.
And again, none of those living at the time will ever forget the media circus with President Bill Clinton, who was convicted of lying about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in office.
Stories of cheating on exams in school and college are commonplace.
There were cases when teachers gave students the answers to the tests to have a good evaluation of the results of their own activities.
Mentors who have to teach the opposite send a message that lies and fraud are acceptable.
How many lies do we face?
Within a day, research shows, you can be lied to 10 to 200 times.
Now it is assumed that a significant part of this is a lie in salvation.
Another study found that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of dating each other.
Detection of a lie or reproof of a lie is a necessary skill for everyone, both for personal and professional purposes.
Unlike a room game, similar to, say, a charade, where you need to shout “Get it!”, the detection of lies is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One result of the study is that most of the old myths about lies have been debunked.
The liars look into the eyes.
They don’t always get stuck, stuttered, reddish or vanish.
It is not necessary to conclude from this that liars are difficult to notice and difficult to expose.
An experienced lie-discoverer can get to the truth by observing the structure of statements, mimics, structure of questions, and temporal characteristics.
I have spent several years researching scientific discoveries in a vast and ever-growing segment of the knowledge of lies, and it is clear that the detection of lies is a modern skill that is easy to learn and that helps to navigate in our complex world -- especially if your professional responsibilities include recruiting, interviewing, and more.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel relaxed, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from the study that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men lie more about themselves, while women lie more about others, usually to protect someone’s feelings that married people lie less to their partners than unmarried ones (but the lie they tell is most often blunt).
We also know that if you are perceived as a cheat, others will feel less guilty about cheating on you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your object.
This is called “determination of the initial state.”
This helps to provide a starting point for assessing the changes further.
Observe the posture, laughter, voice characteristics of your object.
It would be good for you to know if a person is constantly tapping his feet in a normal state, then you will not make unfair accusations when you see a tapping of his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for groups of deceptive verbal and nonverbal actions.
Treat these groups as red flags, not as evidence of deception.
Cheaters can fix the upper part of their body when they try to remember their story, they can put their feet towards the door, lean towards the exit, change their posture in a certain way, or show “relief after the interview” — this exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture when all is difficult.
Investigators often falsify the end-of-interview signal to simply look at this relief after the interview.
So, pay attention to the speech of your object.
It is known that Scott Peterson stepped back and used the past time, claiming that his murdered wife was alive, which led to her searches across the country.
Vaping people can also use distancing in speeches: “I haven’t had a sexual relationship with this woman...Miss Lewinsky” or repeat a complex question altogether.
The most typical verbal indicators are barely catchable.
Someone may use “qualifying language” when answering a difficult question: “Well...in truth...as far as I know...as far as I know.”
This makes the response more emotional than actual, and is often a red flag.
There is no magical means to detect a lie, but it is possible to master the skill of detecting deception.
These skills will increase everyone’s chances of not becoming a victim of skilled scammers in their professional and personal lives.
