Court approves ‘transition to digital television’ in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog signals with digital ones is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court rejected constitutional claims filed by the Senate and House of Representatives against the presidential decree, which postpones the so-called “transition to digital television” from 2021 to 2015, as eight votes were not collected necessary for its annulment.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Mesa, felt that President Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n had not exceeded his powers by issuing a decree detailing actions for the transition to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional claims asserted by the Senate were rejected due to the lack of a qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to pronounce on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft statement, prepared by Minister Olga Sanchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional because the regulation of the radio and television program is a right enshrined in the law of the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted for the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and support the complaints, and Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions mentioned in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
At the ministerial meeting it was also decided to reject the demand of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sanchez Cordero.
In his speech, the prime minister said he disagreed with the project's arguments in the sense that the federal executive cannot determine by common rules the measures to be prepared by the state administration.
“I also do not believe that if this happened, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body,” and recalled that planning public policy in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, is relevant to the federal executive authority, which has a constitutional mandate, state governance.
Replacing analog signals with digital ones is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years, leading to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Delaying the transition, he said, would mean deferring the benefits of transforming into a digital form that includes meeting societal needs that have not only a technical dimension, “as it covers economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These issues, he said, "require the work of the whole system, formed on the principle of state economic management, includes a group of authorities, which the Constitution unites into state executive power."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and have done so with the help of the executive, despite the availability of highly specialized technical institutions.
From this it cannot be concluded that the Government, in adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competences of Congress, ensures in the administrative sphere compliance with the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
