A new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present a new government that will face the crisis that has put the country on the verge of economic disaster.
Italy’s appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with Italy’s president on Wednesday to introduce a new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and hurt the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he could form a government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed mainly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive body will take its position.
Monti said he would present the results of his negotiations with political parties to the president in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to reaffirm my full confidence in our country's ability to get out of this difficult period," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monty did not say directly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
“The structure is well-designed now,” he said.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, as Italy struggled with a political and financial crisis that brought the size of their debt to a critical level.
The administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the austerity package required by European leaders to restore confidence in Italy.
Based on pressure on Monti to hurry, volatile markets set Italy’s 10-year BTP bond yields at more than 7 percent, a level that Greece and Ireland had to save.
Emma Marchegalia, the leader of the Italian Federation of Employers, told reporters after a meeting with Monti: "We said we would actively support this government."
We believe that this government is Italy’s last chance to get out of this critical situation.
Monti’s chances of success were largely based on the support of LDP’s Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday due to the crisis.
“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts should lead to a good outcome,” Angelino Alfano, the secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
Support for the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is important because so far many of its members have opposed the governmental majority, consisting of technocrats, which forms Monti.
Parliamentary backing
The new Monti government should have strong parliamentary support for reforms that are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or suspension of these attempts could lead to a new and destructive attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has stepped up pressure, warning that Monti’s failure could be a disaster.
On Monday, Monty began his consultations with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations.
He will finish his meeting on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who allowed an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italy’s debt cost has now reached a critical level amid uncertainty as to whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Saving Italy with a government debt of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.8 billion would be too much for modern euro zone financial defenders.
Monty said his government would exist until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread projections that politicians would only give him time to reform before appointing a new election.
Monty said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but major parties insist that it should only be made up of technical experts, a testimony to their dissatisfaction with the fact that the process is affected by the financial situation.
Political sources said the mutual distrust and disagreement of the parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
