The quintet included the country in the tour in honor of the twentieth anniversary of his career
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true.
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to give one of the best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
There has been more than 20 years of waiting, but the band says it’s also a dream come true for them to play in this country.
This was the claim of bassist and founder Jeff Ament, who gave an exclusive interview with Viva from Brazil last week.
The group is on the territory of South America as part of a tour in honor of the twentieth anniversary of the work and on Sunday, the 20th, will make its only stop in Central America.
On this day, they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., along with the Los Angeles X team and the local Las Robertas group.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full decryption of which is available online at The Nation.
For your Costa Rican fans it’s a dream come true that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica? Do you know what your fans are experiencing?
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us, too.
This is only our second visit to South and Central America, and so far everything is going well.
I've only been to Costa Rica once - on vacation, it's a beautiful country, and I think we can stay there for a few days.
We are very happy to bring our music there.
I ask about it because there is some loyalty to the band; the fans live in tension in the days before the concert.
What would you say to your most loyal fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, thank you for waiting so long, and we regret that it took us so long to get here.
Some people, in anticipation of your concert, regard it as the biggest show of the year.
Does it add a little tension to your visit?
“Some of the biggest shows we’ve played in the past 21 years have taken place over the last two weeks.
We have had some great shows in S<0xC3><0xA3>o Paulo and we hope this has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play here.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle, as far as these two things are concerned, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you learn about Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of surfing friends, and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo, and the waves here are incredible.
My friends always go surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, as well as in Mexico, these are great places for surfing, this is how we learned about it, from people who love surfing.
Looking at the tour, we can say that you have done a great show with a lot of songs.
What do you plan to do in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there before, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible with a wide variety of songs; we will try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a great variety of repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
How does that work?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs, and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs that we haven’t played for a while, it keeps us in tone and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and what we might have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and so I think it makes it more interesting for people.
This tour marks 20 years of your career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve done?
Yes, of course.
First of all, I think none of us could ever have imagined that we would be in a rock band and the fact that we’ve been doing this for over 20 years makes it look like a dream.
We are very happy with our success and we are very excited that we can continue to create music together.
We all love each other and love to make music.
We are happy to travel to places in the world where we always wanted to go.
Everything is going very well for us.
What does it mean for you to be a significant part of the blossoming of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great collectives.
We are good friends with the guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It’s great when the movement grows out of a group of friends, and it’s unusual.
From time to time, one group appears from the same city, but it is much more strange when five or ten groups appear at the same time in the same city.
We are proud and honoured to be part of the Seattle band.
I still play with some of them from time to time.
