Yes, the producers sent us a few video offers, and it was the band we liked the most, so we can’t wait to see what Las Robertas can offer live, and it should be very exciting.
Why do you constantly change the words in Yellow Ledbetter at concerts?
It's a question to Ed (Eddie Vedder) so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he uses the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
So many of them.
Among the first to come to mind are Heather Butler, John Entwissle, C.J. Ramon, John Dow, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many of them that I can talk all day about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed in maintaining the relevance of the grunge, despite the fact that it is no longer in fashion?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think of him, he reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone that came along at the same time, and if that’s important now, I think it’s great because it’s the music that’s worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are making music better now than ever.
At first your music was darker, and now it has become more positive.
How would you explain this change?
It’s interesting because I think there are a few songs on the album that may seem easier, but there are songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very gloomy, although they may sound a bit positive.
From both of them, when Ed played them, I cried when I listened to them, these songs are very gloomy.
I think when you grow up and you’ve had some kind of trauma in your life and you’ve lost a family member or a friend, these events start to affect your creativity and your music, and these two songs, of course, reflect that to me.
So, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make dark music.
