MSS Announces Obesity Gene Search Program
Social protection leads a study to find the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by specialists from IPN
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young people, which has been dubbed the “Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescence” protocol, which will provide a count of signs associated with overweight.
In his statement, Miguel Cruz Lopez, head of the Department of Medical Research in Biochemistry at the National Medical Center of the 21st Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been assembled.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Health (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (whether prescribed or not) is invited to participate by going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, in the Valley of Mexico, where every Saturday, from 8:00 am, tests with children will be conducted.
He emphasized that the protocol began to be conducted at the sports center in Queuetoque (western state of Mexico), and from October 8 the events are held at the sports center in Nessaualcoyotl (eastern state of Mexico).
Once the target of attracting 500 to 600 children has been reached, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (Southern Mexico) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (Northern Mexico).
He explained that the purpose of this study is to understand the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
On 14 November, World Diabetes Day will be celebrated, and the main goal is to gather three thousand children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 years with the permission of their parents and under their supervision to fill out individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to the onset of diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), measurement of blood pressure and glucose levels, fats, cholesterol and insulin, and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity) will be carried out.
Cruz Lopez said the study reflects health care professionals’ concern about worrying weight gain among children.
In medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006, there was an increase in just 6 years: in the case of boys, 77 per cent suffered from obesity, in the case of girls, 47 per cent; as for excess weight, there was also a significant increase, "said the MSSI expert.
He said that the rationale for searching for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican is 65 percent descended from American Indians, 30 percent from Europeans, and five percent from Africans, and this condition has affected the genes that are associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, basically, the consequence of obesity genetics is the body’s inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and it is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that a direct benefit to participants is a comprehensive assessment of children, which can identify whether they have any degree of excess weight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark wrinkles on the neck (acants) and forearms means the likelihood of a metabolic disorder and even prediabetes.
The information is treated with complete confidentiality, the doctors pass it on in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the dimensions and lifestyle changes that must be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main causes of overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of the TV, and using transportation at short distances instead.
This is also due to the high calorie intake, that is, the increase in the consumption of sweet drinks and carbohydrates (tamala, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetic predisposition analyzed in this program.
Asphalt UNAM can avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, has developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a blend of the best quality, resistant to environmental and temperature exposure.
If the signals sent by the road surface were paid attention, then it would be necessary to repair about 200,000 pits for each rainy season in the metropolitan area of the Valley of Mexico, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, a researcher at the UNAM chemical faculty, and adds that if the process of construction and construction
In his lecture, The Technological Look at Wells, read within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing a polymer-modified bitumen for the production of a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and, therefore, to counteract the formation of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of which are high molecular weight, called asphalts, and others of which are low molecular weight, called malts, which together give the road surface its characteristic viscosity.
The viscous behavior of bitumen is the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it retains an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, bitumen becomes clumpy.
This means that the resistance of the street asphalt is not constant, but changes during the day, depending on the natural conditions and temperature, said the specialist in chemical engineering.
A chimfaq scientist noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible coating, which consists of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the topmost layers is bitumen, made up of small stones, dropped into bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is submerged in bitumen.
When moving vehicles and exerting effort, it helps the forces to be very well distributed along the road surface.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would be even better distributed, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt coating, he added, the last layer, which is called the wear layer, is made of fine stone, in fact the sand is also submerged in the asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will come into contact with the wheels of the transport, it should have more resistance than the asphalt coating and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute these efforts, the wear layer also requires an appropriate thickness and it is necessary to take into account the material from which it is made.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the state of the asphalt.
When the soil is raw, the water penetrates the coating and it is difficult for it to get out of there, it causes the softening of all layers of the coating and, therefore, the formation of pits.
When forming pits, he said, the first layer of wear wears out and only then it affects the bitumen, but the damage does not occur immediately, it is a process that should be paid attention to at the first signs under the programs of current repair.
Also, a member of the National System of Researchers explained that the transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of coating should always be associated with the transport load and it is necessary to ensure that this requirement is met to prevent the frequent appearance of holes.
Rafael Herrera said that with regard to bitumen, much still needs to be studied and done, for example, bitumen emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries and even help to repair pits with ease and without the use of high temperatures.
