The Energy Policy:
The facts must prevail over the dogmas.
If there is a topic on which a decision cannot be made after a short discussion or under the influence of emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is a healthy trend that election meetings are becoming an occasion to reflect on the share and place occupied by nuclear energy.
The dispute will not bear fruit until all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options have been studied.
France must build its opinion on objective facts and rational data.
With 7 billion people on the planet, demographic development will double the need for electricity by 2050, unless a huge part of the world’s population is deprived of vital elements.
During the same period, it will be necessary to compensate for the growing shortage of fossil resources in order to continue the production of electricity continuously, not forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate imbalance - a topic that has disappeared from the environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these factors.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to abandon nuclear power.
This is not the case of Belgium, which makes its decision dependent on the need to find a source capable of replacing nuclear energy, or Switzerland, which intends to build only the most modern reactors.
On the other hand, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil are just a few of those who are resolutely continuing their projects.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add one plant to its set, resuming the construction of the station, which was interrupted after the accident on Tri-Mill Island.
Although Germany’s model based on renewable energy is sometimes cited as an example, reality contradicts this argument.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the cost of electricity, increased energy dependence, exacerbated by the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, the rise in carbon dioxide emissions due to the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all these unpleasant effects will already be noticeable.
Consider the example of Denmark.
The European champion in the construction of turbines, from which it receives 30% of its electricity, it is also the largest consumer of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; due to which the emissions of carbon dioxide and electricity prices are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the average in Europe.
On the other hand, thanks to the persistence of our energy policy, our neighbours pay 40% more for electricity than French households.
Since in a globalized economy the price of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of service of industrial equipment on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in nuclear power will lead to a great increase in the cost of electricity, which will make illusory beautiful statements about the new industrialization of our country and the protection of purchasing power.
The price that most French people refuse to pay, especially because they do not object to this kind of energy in principle.
It should be remembered that the country's energy policy has made it possible to create an industry with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect ones.
Strongly export-oriented, it attracts a whole host of specialized international trade small and medium-sized enterprises and creates many jobs that cannot be moved to another industry.
If France decided to give up nuclear power, it would have to donate a large number of these enterprises and lose <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6 billion a year from French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrical engineer would order an EPR, designed to work for sixty years, if it was planned to close its manufacturer?
In order to solve the energy equation, one must recognize that there are no divine or devilish sources of energy production.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the interoperability of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest level of security for nuclear energy is undoubtedly a vital issue
In France, we have a security body that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing energy centres such as Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is generally recognized, are full of the same obsession with safety.
For 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major incidents.
Only one, Tri-Mill Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, but without any consequences for humans or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the device of the reactor and the unforgivable human error led to the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident occurred as a result of two natural disasters of unprecedented force that resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw lessons from this accident, as it has drawn from the two previous ones.
The fruit of this step and the cooperation between the security authorities, the operators and the French and German designers, EPR, presents a project to counter such phenomena.
