The difference is only in the level of generosity that they allow to show to immigrants.
In his program, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande confined himself to banality, saying that “joint work will solve our immigration problem.”
This notion of immigration as both a burden and a problem can give an electoral advantage, but economically it is very expensive.
As we are reminded by economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron in a recent book, which summarized the latest data on immigration (Special people: How migration shaped our world and will determine our future, May 2011, the publisher of Princeton University Growth, 352 c.), there is a broad consensus among experts.
Restriction of immigration leads to weakened growth and reduced employment.
Fears of the influence of immigrants are based on the notion that they are able to replace local workers, especially low-skilled ones, provoking lower wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants supplement much more than they replace the local workforce, performing jobs for which the local workforce is lacking.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local labour, and the most skilled - in dynamic sectors where training is not linked to job offers.
Positive impact on wages
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, the complementarity existing between locals and immigrants leads to the fact that the arrival of immigrants positively affects the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Peri estimated that a 1% increase in the migration flow leads to an increase of 0.6-0.9% in real long-term wages.
And this is without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of new ideas and economic growth (among the American Nobel laureates, a large proportion of naturalized immigrants, and Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo - all were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also bring net profits to social security systems, giving an average of 1% of the total budgets of European countries.
According to the World Labour Organization, for example, in Germany, an immigrant, arriving at the age of 30, will bring the state budget a net profit (income minus expenses) of an average of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 in his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy at the beginning of his term was going to cling to the missing growth points with his "toothes".
The aforementioned teeth, which were used to scare off immigrants, gave exactly the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, it remains to understand European democracy
Democracy is a valuable acquisition, but at the same time it is fragile.
The European continent must remember that, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, in the 20th century it experienced the tragedies of World War I, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, Gulag, as well as Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and colonels in Greece.
Some believed that in order for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it was enough to arrange a vote and make it as direct as possible.
