The North Stream, a new gateway for the entry of Russian gas into Europe.
The North Stream pipeline connecting Western Europe and Russia directly to the bottom of the Baltic Sea has been launched.
It is designed to supply the equivalent of 30 million households with gas.
Gazprom, a Russian giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate this event with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between the orchestra’s performance and exquisite snacks, in the opening of the Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany underwater.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch colleague, Mart Rutte, together turned the symbolic valve controlling the inflow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
Under the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of gas will be supplied to Western Europe each year via the first 1,224 km long pipeline connecting the Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
The second pipeline is expected to be ready by the end of 2012, providing a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas equivalent to all of France’s consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met with fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream will indeed deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power: it will be harder for them to influence Russia, threatening to shut down access to Western European markets.
At the most tense moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop before comparing the North Stream with the new "German-Soviet Pact", hinting at an alliance between Hitler and Stalin with the aim of occupying Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is striving for greater security of supply.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to achieve its understanding of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western countries, which consume large volumes of gas and whose own reserves are already at an end.
“This gas pipeline is part of the cooperation with Russia, it’s a new artery that organically connects us,” said Francois Fillon, opening the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Lubmin, the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel enclosed in concrete to protect it from ship anchors.
It lies at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to bypass the minefields left from the Second World War.
“A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
There was also a need to take many steps to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metallic snake with a weight equal to 242 Eiffel Towers, without breaks along its entire length, without valves and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers abandoned it because Sweden was not thrilled that the Russian state-owned company would settle off its shores forever.
“In the event of an accident, we will cut off the flow of gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
So, in case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline will go into the air.
But this seems unlikely to the designers who designed the seams designed to leak only once every 100,000 years.
Control over the state of the gas pipeline will be carried out by an underwater robot, which pulls the ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
The cigar-shaped apparatus is introduced into the pipeline with a diameter of 1 meter and pushed forward by the flow of gas.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, it gives accurate information about any deformation of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the need for any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is carried out only at the expense of its pressure.
It is 200 bar on departure and 100 bar on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), the Dutch Gasunie and the French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies set up a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was commissioned to build and operate the pipeline.
Its headquarters are located in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Then Gazprom leased this company for twenty years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
“Gasprom will pay for the full volume, regardless of how much gas is actually being transported,” says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by 30% shareholders and by 70% bank loans.
The total cost of the works will be 7.4 thousand million euros for two pipelines.
The investment of GDF Suez will be around 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will pay for their costs, because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The pipeline exits from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin to a sandy shore planted with conifers.
The valves 4.5 meters high form the gas outlet terminal.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before pumping it into German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has received one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity it will be 3 million per hour, and in 2012 6 million.
Moleskine brand notebook
Moleskine, created by an Italian company fifteen years ago, will return the taste of the letter.
It has the scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notepad is easy to recognize by the rectangular black cover, the rubber band, the yellowish-white pages, as if yellowed over time.
However, Moleskine’s notebook, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, located in Milan, decided to launch the design notebooks for sale.
Maria Sebregondi, the then consultant of the company, took responsibility for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique, moleskin - lacquered cotton fabric, used, for example, to cover the bedsheets.
It is claimed that this type of notebook is highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine brought into line with today’s taste the old and forgotten thing that was a cult for avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the managing director of Modo Modo.
Success is here.
From 2006 to 2010, sales increased by 25% to reach 12.7 million units.
We have gone far from the production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine has crossed the borders of Italy and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
Setting up a typical buyer profile is difficult, because the notebook equally attracts a businessman, a student, and a freelancer.
Moleskine buyers are cosmopolitan, broad-minded and educated.
The small Italian company, which initially had only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in Fnac bookstores, shops in the centers of small towns and has been able to gain widespread fame.
“We have followed the spirit of time and this new need in the letter, despite the advent of email,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This characteristic cultural trait accompanies the development of Moleskine; the brand recently organized the exhibition "The Round Path", where architects and artists showed their own notebooks.
In August, he also released leopard-painted covers for the Locarno Film Festival.
Using its successes and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products, which now include bags, pens, computer bags. The brand includes all kinds of support.
Success that gave rise to envy: in the fall of 2006 Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which made a new page in Moleskine history.
Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week of employment for disabled people begins today.
Despite the public charity policy launched in 2005, the rate of unemployment among persons with disabilities is still twice the average, 19 per cent versus 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Dissatisfied?
“No,” says Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of employment for people with disabilities.
"Serious progress has been made in 15 years."
"At that time, the share of unemployed was not 2, but 3 times more."
“There is still a lot of work ahead.”
I have to say that there is still a lot of obstacles for the disabled in employment.
Among them, more seniors: 37% over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a rather low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor’s degree, and out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85% for people with disabilities versus 38% on average.
In short, all of these are criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and that are the essence of the problem,” said Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about a mentality that is changing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association on behalf of Cité found that the managers surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disability and "imagined solid people in wheelchairs either mentally or mentally disabled."
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from having the goal of having 6% of disabled workers set out in the law adopted in 1987.
The last known figures for 2008 are 2.6 per cent.
“Today we are about 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxable" organizations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased in 2007-2011 from 59,000 to 46,000 organizations (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which raised taxes, put a lot of pressure on the company,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects an increase in awareness, particularly in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organizations with the number of employees from 20 to 49 have disabled employees compared to 82% of organizations with the number of employees from 100 to 199.
